# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#  PROJECT RULES — Next.js + Atomic Design
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

You are an expert Next.js 14 developer. Always follow the rules below strictly.

## Stack
- Framework : Next.js 14 (App Router)
- Language  : TypeScript (strict mode)
- Styling   : Tailwind CSS (mobile-first)
- Icons     : lucide-react

---

## Atomic Design Architecture

All components live under src/components/ and must follow this hierarchy:

```
src/
├── app/                        ← Next.js App Router (pages, layouts, routes)
│   ├── layout.tsx
│   ├── page.tsx
│   └── (routes)/
├── components/
│   ├── atoms/                  ← Smallest building blocks (no business logic)
│   │   ├── Button/
│   │   │   ├── index.tsx
│   │   │   └── Button.types.ts
│   │   ├── Input/
│   │   ├── Icon/
│   │   ├── Text/
│   │   └── Badge/
│   ├── molecules/              ← Combinations of atoms
│   │   ├── SearchBar/
│   │   ├── FormField/
│   │   └── Card/
│   ├── organisms/              ← Complex UI sections, may have local state
│   │   ├── Navbar/
│   │   ├── HeroSection/
│   │   └── Footer/
│   └── templates/              ← Page layouts with slots (no real data)
│       ├── AuthLayout/
│       └── DashboardLayout/
├── hooks/                      ← Custom React hooks
├── lib/                        ← Utilities, helpers, constants
├── types/                      ← Global TypeScript types
└── styles/                     ← Global CSS, Tailwind config overrides
```

---

## Component Rules

### Atoms
- Zero business logic
- No API calls or data fetching
- Accept only primitive or simple typed props
- Must be fully reusable and stateless (or minimal local UI state like hover)
- Example: Button, Input, Label, Icon, Spinner, Avatar

### Molecules
- Combine 2+ atoms
- May have simple local UI state (e.g. open/close toggle)
- No API calls
- Example: SearchBar (Input + Icon), FormField (Label + Input + ErrorText)

### Organisms
- Combine molecules and/or atoms into a meaningful UI section
- May have local state and event handlers passed as props
- No direct API calls (receive data via props)
- Example: Navbar, ProductCard, CommentThread

### Templates
- Define the page layout/skeleton using slots (children props)
- No real data — just structure and spacing
- Example: TwoColumnLayout, AuthPageLayout

### App (Pages)
- Live inside src/app/ following Next.js App Router conventions
- Fetch data here (server components, async functions)
- Compose templates + organisms to build the full page

---

## TypeScript Rules

- Every component must have a typed Props interface in a separate `.types.ts` file
- Use `React.FC<Props>` or explicit return type `JSX.Element`
- No `any` types — ever
- Use `interface` for props, `type` for unions/utility types

Example:
```ts
// Button.types.ts
export interface ButtonProps {
  label: string;
  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary' | 'ghost';
  size?: 'sm' | 'md' | 'lg';
  disabled?: boolean;
  onClick?: () => void;
}
```

---

## Styling Rules (Tailwind — Mobile First)

- Always write mobile styles first, then scale up:
  `className="text-sm md:text-base lg:text-lg"`
- Use Tailwind utility classes only — no inline styles
- For repeated patterns, extract into a component, not a custom CSS class
- Use `cn()` utility (clsx + tailwind-merge) for conditional classNames

```ts
// lib/utils.ts
import { clsx, type ClassValue } from 'clsx'
import { twMerge } from 'tailwind-merge'

export function cn(...inputs: ClassValue[]) {
  return twMerge(clsx(inputs))
}
```

---

## File & Naming Conventions

- Component folders: PascalCase  → `Button/`, `SearchBar/`
- Component files : `index.tsx` inside the folder
- Types file      : `ComponentName.types.ts`
- Hooks           : camelCase starting with `use` → `useAuth.ts`
- Utilities       : camelCase → `formatDate.ts`
- Pages           : lowercase with hyphens (Next.js convention) → `app/about-us/page.tsx`

---

## When Creating a New Component — Always Ask:

1. Which atomic layer does this belong to? (atom / molecule / organism / template)
2. Does it need its own types file?
3. Is it truly reusable or page-specific?
4. Should it be a Server Component or Client Component?
   - Default to Server Component
   - Add `'use client'` only if it needs: useState, useEffect, event listeners, browser APIs

---

## Code Style

- Always add a comment at the top of each component describing what it is and its layer
- Keep components under 150 lines — split if larger
- Prefer named exports over default exports for components
- Group imports: React → Next.js → Third-party → Internal → Types → Styles

---

## Design Guidelines (Mobile-First)

- Design for 375px screen width first
- Touch targets must be minimum 44x44px
- Use sufficient color contrast (WCAG AA minimum)
- Avoid hover-only interactions — always have a tap-friendly alternative
- Prefer bottom-of-screen navigation for mobile (thumb-friendly)
